<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/J-GNQizY_sWwhTc9Zr5jNLDPORU=/0x0:3072x2048/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/VqcGxs4Y5B4F37CzJfXwjKllC3A=/0x0:3072x2048/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/hLfD1WvxVuJyx3i2EMCjf3UzHPo=/0x0:3072x2048/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/_4Vp6s2VFsmn64xmzGX4rMiLVZI=/0x0:3072x2048/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/YrDiLp9_CgRECQCUiXR10Llm7OM=/0x0:3072x2048/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/c5qIafAz3ZEnmX_L0QQTy0bpBOo=/0x0:3072x2048/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/lwp9JiP23X0gAd5c3UXuDBvWwAI=/0x0:3072x2048/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/9i2hgeb6k6xfZaM7kNYrrTT3XPM=/0x0:3072x2048/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ZZ1AnXAcn1KMvJa9UwnD2R7Q2bE=/0x0:3072x2048/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="President Ronald Reagan signs the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981,&amp;nbsp;while on vacation at his ranch named Rancho del Cielo." data-upload-width="3072" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/IOdorVhnudoX6hdjpuosrEEhuDk=/0x0:3072x2048/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:3072x2048):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969837/GettyImages_50538608.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption>President Ronald Reagan signs the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981, slashing the top income tax rate by 20 points.</figcaption>
      
      
        <cite>Dirck Halstead/The LIFE Images Collection/Getty Images</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="PCssnS">A desire to slash deficits led George H.W. Bush to conclude that a 28 percent top rate was infeasibly low, prompting him to <a href="https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/laws-proposals/major-enacted-tax-legislation-1990-1999#omnibus-budget-reconciliation-act-of-1990">boost it to 31 percent</a> when he famously violated his “no new taxes” pledge in 1990. Shortly after taking office in 1993, <a href="https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/laws-proposals/major-enacted-tax-legislation-1990-1999#omnibus-budget-reconciliation-act-of-1993">Bill Clinton added 36 percent and 39.6 percent brackets</a>.</p>
<p id="o1j8Mk">Fights over the top income tax rate ever since have taken place in a very narrow band between 35 and 39.6 percent. George W. Bush cut it to 35 in 2001; Obama forced House Republicans to agree to restore it to 39.6 percent in late 2012; Donald Trump and his congressional allies brought it back down to 37 percent in 2017.</p>
<p id="uqlLTf">The Affordable Care Act <em>did</em> include a small 0.9 percent surtax on wages for wealthy individuals, which put their effective top rate (including the existing 2.9 percent Medicare payroll tax) at 43.4 percent by the time Obama left office; Trump’s tax cuts took that number down to 40.8 percent.</p>
<p id="sNUM7V">The estate tax has seen a <a href="https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/statistics/exemption-level-1916-2017">similar trajectory</a>, stagnating at 55 percent between the first Reagan tax cuts and George W. Bush. The 2001 tax cuts then set it on course to be totally abolished — and it was for one year, 2010, a truly great year for rich people to die in — only to see it resurrected with lower top rates (35 percent and 40 percent) after the 2010 and 2012 budget battles.</p>
  <figure class="e-image">
  <span class="e-image__inner">
    
    <span class="e-image__image " data-original="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg">
      
        <picture class="c-picture" data-cid="site/picture_element-1587272114_153_58907" data-cdata='{"asset_id":15969874,"ratio":"*"}'>
  


  <source srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/zF4DVUa794EtIbllMwHc5YECqvY=/0x0:2000x1312/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/XvDpSFXAbZQqP6crhTSNYEGS8kM=/0x0:2000x1312/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/sqwDnmIWZuJibH6PdQIk1MT6AOM=/0x0:2000x1312/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/LdvpUtkvdQH8zMt_-SP1EIk6XZ8=/0x0:2000x1312/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/6Ah5QkEoATK7a4QRIr2dOYkh1fE=/0x0:2000x1312/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/ygcSQ7pFi2eMkZBQXYY1Ilv4Zss=/0x0:2000x1312/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/bzTN9Eh1ULYUFUW3BLJHAUmXook=/0x0:2000x1312/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/GomrMpZBIzU1_F0yfoAaJNVDVbU=/0x0:2000x1312/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/QLpQiNTo7F2gUjMv9t0wlZ_UKXk=/0x0:2000x1312/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):format(webp):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" type="image/webp">


<img srcset="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/FJBQOq51yOLHypnydKRF7LuLjmA=/0x0:2000x1312/320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/fMj4LMiLfotsZK46QjgghCJDWfs=/0x0:2000x1312/520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2Oh0ecATx-CE9gqRLlBzNDs3iPk=/0x0:2000x1312/720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/62C0lveFoguATLJOLo5e6ot20O8=/0x0:2000x1312/920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 920w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HJsn7DvFaksCv0QGWGVxLqfzZN8=/0x0:2000x1312/1120x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1120w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/VnmASk0nGsy0jbvAteJXMh1An1w=/0x0:2000x1312/1320x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1320w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/GVDDhO1gusAhuEFKitDdeDLTYQo=/0x0:2000x1312/1520x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1520w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/mjl1XOnguYs-CASjABSeQGND12o=/0x0:2000x1312/1720x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1720w, https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/OajCy-9hXPK1Y93wL9wKF5KVRD4=/0x0:2000x1312/1920x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg 1920w" sizes="(min-width: 1221px) 846px, (min-width: 880px) calc(100vw - 334px), 100vw" alt="President George W. Bush during a five day, two state trip through Arkansas and Georgia promoting his 1.6 trillion dollar tax cut, on March 1, 2001." data-upload-width="2000" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7A6VhYAxkLnbm66CsmBbN_i7_fk=/0x0:2000x1312/1200x0/filters:focal(0x0:2000x1312):no_upscale()/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15969874/GettyImages_908495.jpg">

</source></picture>

      
    </span>
    
  </span>
  
    <span class="e-image__meta">
      
        <figcaption>President George W. Bush during a five-day, two-state trip through Arkansas and Georgia promoting his $1.6 trillion tax cut, on March 1, 2001.</figcaption>
      
      
        <cite>Erik S. Lesser/Newsmakers via Getty Images</cite>
      
    </span>
  
</figure>

<p id="1YTPXN">Obama proposed other measures to increase taxation on top earners that Congress never gave a hearing, but they were modest compared to the ideas that Sanders, Ocasio-Cortez, and Warren are floating now. His two principal ideas were the “Buffett Rule” — a minimum tax rate of 30 percent for people with $1 million-plus in income, <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2011/08/15/opinion/stop-coddling-the-super-rich.html">inspired by Warren Buffett</a> — and a <a href="https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/taxvox/obamas-cap-tax-deductions-not-what-it-seems">cap on itemized deductions and exclusions</a>. The Buffett Rule would’ve dramatically <a href="https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/taxvox/how-would-buffett-rule-affect-marginal-tax-rates">increased the tax rate on investment income</a>, but only to the mid-30s range. Neither plan would’ve raised the top rate on wage income to anything like its historic highs.</p>
<p id="9FnVIh">Obama certainly wanted to increase taxes on the rich more than he did. But even his most ambitious proposals were <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/17/business/for-economists-saez-and-piketty-the-buffett-rule-is-just-a-start.html">not really scaled to substantially cut inequality</a> or raise a huge amount of revenue. The new generation of Democratic proposals are.</p>
<h3 id="VhVnOD">The intellectual basis for taxing the rich</h3>
<p id="F5xkYd">So what accounts for the new aggressive support for taxing the rich among leading Democrats? There’s the Great Recession, in which bankers were bailed out as high unemployment persisted for years; and the Occupy movement, which made economic inequality a core national issue in 2011 and onward.</p>
  <figure class="e-image">
  <span class="e-image__inner">
    
    <span class="e-image__image " data-original="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/15970042/GettyImages_180884226.jpg">
      
